We use a D-efficiency method, which follows the standard principle of seeking a set of experimental treatments which minimize the asymptotic covariance of the treatment effect estimates given a fixed sample size. We follow standard practice in the discrete choice econometric literature and base our D-efficiency design on a conditional logit model [39, 40], in which the probability of an experimental subject selecting stove j from a choice set t is:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
